FELINE SPONGIFORM ENCEPHALOPATHY: CURRENT STATUS
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Feline spongiform encephalopathy 960610
Date: Mon, 2 Mar 1998 10:30:42 -0600
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj2020@vt8200.vetmed.lsu.edu>

The following report has been assembled from various sources. While this
disease seemed to be disappearing, its death has certainly been exaggerated.
Obviously, the clinical recognition of cases is variable and submission of
the appropriate feline tissues to the Pathology Department, CVL, MAFF, for a
confirmatory diagnosis is another quasi-random factor. If the externalities
affecting the recognition and diagnosis of this condition are not
overwhelming, the annual incidence would appear to be decreasing. A
suggestion as to why the condition may have been prolonged may be regarded
as controversial by some.
<http://www.maff.gov.uk/animalh/bse/bse-statistics/level-3-tsestat.html>
Feline Spongiform Encephalopathy
total to date: 81 (plus one in Northern Ireland, one in Norway, and one in
Lichtenstein)
Year Cases
1990 12
1991 12
1992 10
1993 11
1994 16
1995 8
1996 6
1997 6 (data up to 1.1.98, there are no records or reports prior to 1990)
--
Martin Hugh-Jones
ProMED-AHEAD Moderator

[2
Date: Sun, 1 Mar 1998 02:52:38 -0500
From: Robert A. LaBudde <ral@lcfltd.com>
Source: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@RZ.UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>

>>I was just last Monday told by Dr.Zeidler from the WHO (while talking with
him at the Blood safety and screening conference in McLean VA.) that the
number of cats in the UK with FSE has stayed at a constant level yearly and
that this is a bit of a puzzle as to why that is. My suggestion was that
even though the cat food has been "cleaned up" and no longer contains
ruminant meat in the UK they probably are still being given "table scraps."
What cat lover does not share tasty morsels from their plate with their cats
at dinner-time? . I'm sure the cat fanciers in the UK dote on their cats no
less than I do. This in turn could be an ominous sign of what is still on
people's dinner plates in the UK.<<
a. UK-FSE has NOT stayed at a constant level, but has declined:
b. The decline is very slow, which is troubling. Also the ramp-up does not
follow the shape of the BSE epidemic. The number of BSE cases has dropped by
10x, but the FSE cases have only gone down by 2x.
c. Cats eat a considerable quantity of meat in their feed. It is doubtful
that this is very significantly augmented by "table scraps". In addition, if
it were, this would have been a clear epidemiological factor that would have
been identified easily in the cases found.
[If the USA is anything to go by, the present quality of wet and dry
commercial cat food is such as to not necessitate feeding them table scraps.
Part of their present much improved longevity these days - twenty years is
not unusual - is thanks to this food quality. In response to a query by
myself to Bob that the early literature had this condition disappearing if
not disappeared, he replied:
This is MAFF wishful thinking. In the Nov. 1996 report, p. 21, they state:
"Six cases of FSE have so far been recorded in 1996, one of which has
occurred in a cat born after the extension of the SBO ban in September 1990.
The cat was found as a stray aged approximately 6 months and consequently
details of the cat's early feeding history are not available."
This would create the impression that no further cases in cats would occur,
and this one was a fluke with poor provenance.
In the June 1997 MAFF report, p. 27, they state:
"The number of cases of feline spongiform encephalopathy (FSE) confirmed
each year in domestic cats continues to fall; there have been only two since
the last Progress Report."
This would imply a dramatic drop was occurring, but in the end there were 6
cases also in 1997, the same as in 1997. No more mention of the case
histories of the cats and their birth dates. I would interpret this as
negative information, since MAFF would have used it if it was positive.
I find it interesting that ANY cases are occurring.
--
