[A suggestion as to the prolonged tail on this feline epidemic. - Mod.MHJ
Date: Mon, 2 Mar 1998 08:38:17 +0000
From: Oz <Oz@upthorpe.demon.co.uk>
Source: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@RZ.UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>

Well, cats live for a couple of decades so one might have expected a long
tail, particularly if the infectivity is very dose dependent.
However I was under the impression (from the odd reports, particularly the
Dalgetty/Spillers debacle in Belgium) that those cat food manufacturers who
continued to use MBM after the initial FSE cases sourced their MBM from
exclusively EU produced (i.e. NOT UK) sources. The added cost is minute and
exactly the thing that a pet food manufacturer would do to protect his
market. As an owner of two fine cats I found this reassuring.
Now, however, I am not sure I would want to eat very much EU (i.e. not UK
produced) beef. Combined with the rather convincing evidence of considerable
EU BSE concealment it looks uncomfortably like more evidence, however
circumstantial and downright speculative.
--
Oz
Holtz de Baar, UK
[However the cooking procedures for processing MBM in Europe appear to be
more rigorous. And if their MBM were "infectious" for cats, a parallel
epidemiological situation would be expected in the European cattle fed this
MBM as calves. Given a choice in a situation of extreme ignorance, the
suggestion that the 'tail' is from prolonged incubation periods would seem
to have merit. - Mod.MHJ

[4
Date: Mon, 2 Mar 1998 10:30:42 -0600
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj2020@vt8200.vetmed.lsu.edu>

The following slightly out-of-date account of FSE was taken from the
MAFF/UK website.
<http://www.maff.gov.uk/animalh/bse/index.html>
Feline Spongiform Encephalopathy
Feline spongiform encephalopathy (FSE) was first identified in Britain in
1990. Since then there have been 81 cases in Great Britain, one in Northern
Ireland, one in Norway and one in Liechtenstein. FSE is not an easy disease
to study. Although Britain has a large cat population they would not
normally have been subjected to close neurological examination in the past.
Nevertheless, sufficient numbers have been seen and investigated to permit
an association with BSE to be made. Obtaining lifetime feeding history for
cats is not easy, so although all have eaten foods that would be expected to
contain specified bovine offals, no particular type of food can be implicated.
Because of this the epidemic in cats is often thought to be a useful model
for past human exposure to BSE. It is currently in decline, and only one cat
has been confirmed that was born after September 1990 when the use of
specified bovine offals in pet food was prohibited.
Although MAFF has not historically had responsibility for investigating
disease in domestic animals, other than rabies, most of the information
gathered about FSE in domestic cats and zoo animals has been provided
through the good will of owners and veterinary practitioners. Laboratory
diagnosis of a spongiform encephalopathy in any species has however been
notifiable since November 1994, thus ensuring that cases were not missed.
Interestingly, brain tissue from some of the early cats identified with FSE
was inoculated into mice. The pattern of incubation periods and lesion
profiles in the mice was indistinguishable from BSE.
In exotic cats there have now been six cases in cheetahs (three were
diagnosed abroad but originated in Britain, three in pumas, one in a tiger
and one in an ocelot.
References:
Pearson G. R. et al. 1992. Feline spongiform encephalopathy: fibril and
PrP studies. Veterinary Record. 131. 307-310.
Wyatt. J. M. et al. 1991. Naturally occurring scrapie-like spongiform
encephalopathy in five domestic cats. Veterinary Record. 129. 233.
Gruffydd-Jones T. J. et al. 1991. Feline spongiform encephalopathy. J. Small
Animal Practice. 33. 471-476.
Willoughby K. 1992. Spongiform encephalopathy in a captive puma (Felis
concolor). Veterinary Record. 131. 431-434.
